# GreetQ Enterprise Architecture & Token-Optimization Rules

## 1. Token & output optimization (strict efficiency)

- **Be concise:** Do not write long conversational introductions, conclusions, or polite prose. Dive straight into the code or solution.
- **Dry / no explanations:** Do not explain *how* the code works unless explicitly asked. The code must speak for itself.
- **Code diffs only:** Never rewrite an entire 300-line file just to change 5 lines. Provide only the modified functions or clear, targeted code diffs.
- **No inline comment bloat:** Avoid obvious comments (e.g. `// setting state`). Only comment on highly complex business logic or edge cases.

## 2. Tech stack & architecture

- **Frontend / backend:** Next.js (App Router), React, TailwindCSS, TypeScript.
- **Database & auth:** Supabase (using `@supabase/ssr` for auth and Next.js Middleware).
- **Validation:** Strict runtime data validation via Zod schemas on all API inputs and Server Actions.

## 3. Enterprise engineering standards

- **Zero trust security:**
  - Never expose `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` to the client. Frontend must only use `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`.
  - Never trust the client to pass its own `user_id` blindly; always verify the user's identity server-side via Supabase auth cookies/metadata.
- **Serverless DB resilience:** Enforce a strict singleton pattern for database client instances to prevent Vercel serverless function connection pool exhaustion.
- **No `any` types:** Strict TypeScript compilation. Every parameter, data model, and API payload must have explicit interfaces or Zod infer types.
- **Websocket safety:** All Supabase Realtime channel subscriptions must include comprehensive cleanup/unmount returns in `useEffect` to prevent memory leaks.

## 4. UI/UX experience principles

- **No layout shifts:** Never use plain text "Loading..." flags. Replace them with animated Tailwind `animate-pulse` skeleton loaders matching the exact dimensions of the target components.
- **Idempotency & double clicks:** All forms and CTA buttons must explicitly leverage pending states, applying `:disabled` layout treatments and `cursor-not-allowed` pointer modifications during asynchronous network requests.
- **Error handling:** Wrap client layouts in functional Error Boundaries. All async failures must trigger responsive UI alerts (e.g., toast messages) instead of silently crashing the interface.

## Codebase anchors (match existing patterns)

| Topic | File |
|-------|------|
| Supabase SSR (server) | `src/lib/supabase/server.ts` |
| Supabase browser client | `src/lib/supabase/client.ts` |
| Admin / service role (server-only) | `src/lib/supabase/admin.ts` |
| Middleware auth | `src/middleware.ts` |
| Zod API validation | e.g. `src/app/api/make/outreach/daily/route.ts` |
| Skeleton loaders | `src/components/ui/Skeleton.tsx`, `src/components/ui/PageLoadingSkeleton.tsx` |
| Error boundary | `src/app/dashboard/error.tsx` |
| Strict TS | `tsconfig.json` (`strict: true`) |
